# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pyside-binding
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] A **foreign function interface** (**FFI**) is a mechanism by which a program written in one programming language can call interoperable routines or make use of services written or compiled in another one.
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] An FFI is often used in contexts where calls are made into a binary dynamic-link library.
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] The term comes from the specification for Common Lisp, which explicitly refers to the programming language feature enabling for inter-language calls as such; the term is also often used officially by the interpreter and compiler documentation for Haskell, Rust, PHP, Python, and LuaJIT (Lua).
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] Other languages use other terminology: Ada has *language bindings*, while Java has *Java Native Interface* (JNI), *Java Native Access* (JNA), or since Java 22, Foreign Function and Memory API.
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] Foreign function interface has become generic terminology for mechanisms which provide such services.
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] The primary function of a foreign function interface is to mate the semantics and calling conventions of one programming language (the *host* language, or the language which defines the FFI), with the semantics and conventions of another (the *guest* language).
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] This process must also take into consideration the runtime environments and application binary interfaces of both.
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] C++ offers compatibility with C trivially, however as C++ uses name mangling, symbols that are to be exported in shared libraries must be wrapped in extern "C" blocks which prevent name mangling.
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] `extern "C"` functions may call C++ code internally, but may only return C types and may not throw exceptions.
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] Many FFIs can be generated automatically: for example, SWIG.
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] However, in the case of an extension language a semantic inversion of the relationship of guest and host can occur, when a smaller body of extension language is the guest invoking services in the larger body of host language, such as writing a small plugin for GIMP.
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] Some FFIs are restricted to free standing functions, while others also allow calls of functions embedded in an object or class (often called method calls); some even permit migration of complex datatypes or objects across the language boundary.
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] In most cases, an FFI is defined by a higher-level language, so that it may employ services defined and implemented in a lower-level language, typically a system programming language like C or C++.
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] This is typically done to either access operating system (OS) services in the language in which the OS API is defined, or for performance goals.
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] Many FFIs also provide the means for the called language to invoke services in the host language also.
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] The term foreign function interface is generally not used to describe multi-lingual runtimes such as the Microsoft Common Language Runtime, where a common *substrate* is provided which enables any CLR-compliant language to use services defined in any other.
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] There are some special cases, in which the languages compile into the same bytecode VM, like Clojure and Java, as well as Elixir and Erlang.
[src:pyside-binding/foreign-function-interface] Since there is no interface, it is not an FFI, strictly speaking, while it offers the same functions to the user.
[src:pyside-binding/language-binding] In programming and software design, a **binding** is an application programming interface (API) that provides glue code specifically made to allow a programming language to use a foreign library or operating system service (one that is not native to that language).
[src:pyside-binding/language-binding] Binding generally refers to a mapping of one thing to another.
[src:pyside-binding/language-binding] In the context of software libraries, bindings are wrapper libraries that bridge two programming languages, so that a library written for one language can be used in another language.
[src:pyside-binding/language-binding] Many software libraries are written in system programming languages such as C or C++.
[src:pyside-binding/language-binding] To use such libraries from another language, usually of higher-level, such as Java, Common Lisp, Scheme, Python, or Lua, a binding to the library must be created in that language, possibly requiring recompiling the language's code, depending on the amount of modification needed.
[src:pyside-binding/language-binding] However, most languages offer a foreign function interface, such as Python's and OCaml's `ctypes`, and Embeddable Common Lisp's `cffi` and `uffi`.
[src:pyside-binding/language-binding] For example, Python bindings are used when an extant C library, written for some purpose, is to be used from Python.
[src:pyside-binding/language-binding] Another example is `libsvn` which is written in C to provide an API to access the Subversion software repository.
[src:pyside-binding/language-binding] To access Subversion from within Java code, `libsvnjavahl` can be used, which depends on `libsvn` being installed and acts as a bridge between the language Java and `libsvn`, thus providing an API that invokes functions from `libsvn` to do the work.
[src:pyside-binding/language-binding] Major motives to create library bindings include software reuse, to reduce reimplementing a library in several languages, and the difficulty of implementing some algorithms efficiently in some high-level languages.
[src:pyside-binding/pyside] By 2009, Nokia, the then owners of the Qt toolkit, wanted Python binding available under the LGPL license.
[src:pyside-binding/pyside] Nokia failed to reach an agreement with Riverbank Computing, the developers of the PyQt Python binding.
[src:pyside-binding/pyside] It provided similar functionality, but under the LGPL.
[src:pyside-binding/pyside] PySide version 1 was released in August 2009 under the LGPL by Nokia, then the owner of the Qt toolkit, after it failed to reach an agreement with PyQt developers Riverbank Computing to change its licensing terms to include LGPL as an alternative license.
[src:pyside-binding/pyside] It supported Qt 4 under the operating systems Linux/X11, Mac OS X, Microsoft Windows, Maemo and MeeGo, while the PySide community added support for Android.
[src:pyside-binding/pyside] PySide2 was started by Christian Tismer to port PySide from Qt 4 to Qt 5 in 2015.
[src:pyside-binding/pyside] The project was then folded into the Qt Project.
[src:pyside-binding/pyside] It added support for Qt 6 and removed support for all Python versions older than 3.6.
[src:pyside-binding/pyside] Python from the Boost C++ libraries for the bindings.
[src:pyside-binding/pyside] It later created its own binding generator named Shiboken, to reduce the size of the binaries and the memory footprint.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:pyside-binding/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
[src:pyside-binding/qml] QML elements can be augmented by standard JavaScript both inline and via included .js files.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Elements can also be seamlessly integrated and extended by C++ components using the Qt framework.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] QML is the language; its JavaScript runtime is the custom V4 engine, since Qt 5.2; and Qt Quick is the 2D scene graph and the UI framework based on it.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] These are all part of the Qt Declarative module, while the technology is no longer called Qt Declarative.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] QML and JavaScript code can be compiled into native C++ binaries with the Qt Quick Compiler.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Alternatively there is a QML cache file format which stores a compiled version of QML dynamically for faster startup the next time it is run.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Objects are specified by their type, followed by a pair of braces.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Object types always begin with a capital letter.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] In the example above, there are two objects, a Rectangle; and its child, an Image.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Between the braces, one can specify information about the object, such as its properties.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Properties are specified as property: value.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] In the example above, the Image has a property named `source`, which has been assigned the value `pics/logo.png`.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] The property and its value are separated by a colon.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Each object can be given a special unique property called an id.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Assigning an id enables the object to be referred to by other objects and scripts.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] The first Rectangle element below has an id, `myRect`.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] The second Rectangle element defines its own width by referring to `myRect.width`, which means it will have the same width value as the first Rectangle element.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] An id must begin with a lower-case letter or an underscore, and can contain no characters other than letters, digits, and underscores.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] A property binding specifies the value of a property in a declarative way.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] The property value is automatically updated if the other properties or data values change, following the reactive programming paradigm.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Property bindings are created implicitly in QML whenever a property is assigned a JavaScript expression.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] The following QML uses two property bindings to connect the size of the rectangle to that of otherItem.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] QML extends a standards-compliant JavaScript engine, so any valid JavaScript expression can be used as a property binding.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Bindings can access object properties, make function calls, and even use built-in JavaScript objects like Date and Math.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] States are a mechanism to combine changes to properties in a semantic unit.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] A button for example has a pressed and a non-pressed state, an address book application could have a read-only and an edit state for contacts.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Every element has an "implicit" base state.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Every other state is described by listing the properties and values of those elements which differ from the base state.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Example: In the default state, myRect is positioned at 0,0.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] In the "moved" state, it is positioned at 50,50.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Clicking within the mouse area changes the state from the default state to the "moved" state, thus moving the rectangle.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] State changes can be animated using Transitions.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Animations in QML are done by animating properties of objects.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Properties of type real, int, color, rect, point, size, and vector3d can all be animated.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] QML supports three main forms of animation: basic property animation, transitions, and property behaviors.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] The simplest form of animation is a PropertyAnimation, which can animate all of the property types listed above.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] A property animation can be specified as a value source using the Animation on property syntax.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] This is especially useful for repeating animations.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Usage of QML does not require Qt/C++ knowledge to use, but it can be easily extended via Qt.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Any C++ class derived from QObject can be easily registered as a type which can then be instantiated in QML.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Signal handlers are JavaScript callbacks which allow imperative actions to be taken in response to an event.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] All signal handler names begin with "on".
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Because QML and JavaScript are very similar, almost all code editors supporting JavaScript will work.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] Full support for syntax highlighting, code completion, integrated help, and a WYSIWYG editor are available in the free cross-platform integrated development environment (IDE) Qt Creator since version 2.1 and many other IDEs.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] The qml executable can be used to run a QML file as a script.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] If the QML file begins with a shebang it can be made directly executable.
[src:pyside-binding/qml] However packaging an application for deployment (especially on mobile platforms) generally involves writing a simple C++ launcher and packaging the needed QML files as resources.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt is currently being developed by The Qt Company, a publicly listed company, and the Qt Project under open-source governance, involving individual developers and organizations working to advance Qt.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt is available under both commercial licenses and open-source GPL 2.0, GPL 3.0, and LGPL 3.0 licenses.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt is used for developing graphical user interfaces (GUIs) and multi-platform applications that run on all major desktop platforms and mobile or embedded platforms.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Most GUI programs created with Qt have a native-looking interface, in which case Qt is classified as a *widget toolkit*.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Non-GUI programs can also be developed, such as command-line tools and consoles for servers.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] An example of such a non-GUI program using Qt is the Cutelyst web framework.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt supports various C++ compilers, including the GCC and Clang C++ compilers and the Visual Studio suite.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] It supports other languages with bindings or extensions, such as Python via Python bindings and PHP via an extension for PHP5, and has extensive internationalization support.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt also provides Qt Quick, that includes a declarative scripting language called QML that allows using JavaScript to provide the logic.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] With Qt Quick, rapid application development for mobile devices became possible, while logic can still be written with native code as well to achieve the best possible performance.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Other features include SQL database access, XML parsing, JSON parsing, thread management and network support.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] The latest version of the Qt Framework is Qt 6.11, which was released on 23 March 2026.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Also still supported are versions 6.10 until 7 October 2026 and 6.8 LTS until 8 October 2029.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Version 6.5 LTS is supported for commercial users only until 3 April 2026.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Additionally, extended support for all versions 5.0 (released in 2012) and newer is available for commercial users.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Minor versions of Qt are typically released twice a year and are supported until one year after release date under standard support conditions.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Typically, every third minor version becomes a long-term support version which gets additional patches.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] LTS versions are supported for commercial users until five years after their release date (three years prior to version 6.8).
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] In 2017, the Qt Company estimated a community of about 1 million developers worldwide in over 70 industries.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] When first released, Qt used its own paint engine and controls, emulating the look of the different platforms it runs on when it drew its widgets.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] This made the porting work easier because very few classes in Qt really depended on the target platform; however, this occasionally led to slight discrepancies where that emulation was imperfect.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Recent versions of Qt use the native style APIs of the different platforms, on platforms that have a native widget set, to query metrics and draw most controls, and do not suffer from such issues as often.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] On some platforms (such as MeeGo and KDE) Qt *is* the native API.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Some other portable graphical toolkits have made different design decisions; for example, wxWidgets uses the toolkits of the target platform for its implementations.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Signals and slots are a language construct introduced in Qt for communication between objects which makes it easy to implement the observer pattern while avoiding boilerplate code.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] The concept is that GUI widgets can send signals containing event information which can be received by other controls using special functions known as slots.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] The metaobject compiler, termed *moc*, is a tool that is run on the sources of a Qt program.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] It interprets certain macros from the C++ code as annotations, and uses them to generate added C++ code with meta information about the classes used in the program.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] This meta information is used by Qt to provide programming features not available natively in C++: signals and slots, introspection and asynchronous function calls.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt moc does not recognise modules in its preprocessor currently.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt can be used in several programming languages other than C++, such as Python, JavaScript, C# and Rust via language bindings; many languages have bindings for Qt 5 and bindings for Qt 4.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] In 2025 The Qt Company announced a new "bridging technology" that aimed to re-think the way of interacting with new languages, listing that a proof of concept was being worked on for integrating C#, Rust, Swift, Java/Kotlin, and Python.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Starting with Qt 4.0 the framework was split into individual modules.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] With Qt 5.0 the architecture was modularized even further.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt is now split into *essential* and *add-on* modules.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt classes by default do not reside in any namespace, but all classes are prefixed with the letter Q.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt can be configured to be compiled to reside in a user-defined namespace.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt is entirely provided through header files, and does not currently support C++ modules.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] There are four editions of Qt available: *Community*, *Indie Mobile*, *Professional* and *Enterprise*.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] The Community version is under the open source licenses, while the Indie Mobile, Professional and Enterprise versions, which contain additional functionality and libraries, e.g.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Enterprise Controls are commercially sold by The Qt Company.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] After Nokia opened the Qt source code to the community on Gitorious, various ports appeared.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] There are also some ports of Qt that may be available, but are not supported anymore.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] These platforms are listed in List of platforms supported by Qt.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] See also there for current community support for other lesser known platforms, such as SailfishOS.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt is available under the following free software licenses: GPL 2.0, GPL 3.0, LGPL 3.0 and LGPL 2.1 (with Qt special exception).
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Note that some modules are available only under a GPL license, which means that applications which link to these modules need to comply with that license.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] In addition, Qt has always been available under a commercial license, like the Qt Commercial License, that allows developing proprietary applications with no restrictions on licensing.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt comes with its own set of tools to ease cross-platform development, which can otherwise be cumbersome due to different set of development tools.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt Creator is a cross-platform IDE for C++ and QML.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt Designer's GUI layout/design functionality is integrated into the IDE, although Qt Designer can still be started as a standalone tool.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] In addition to Qt Creator, Qt provides qmake, a cross-platform build script generation tool that automates the generation of Makefiles for development projects across different platforms.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] There are other tools available in Qt, including the Qt Designer interface builder and the Qt Assistant help browser (which are both embedded in Qt Creator), the Qt Linguist translation tool, uic (user interface compiler), and moc (Meta-Object Compiler).
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] In the summer of 1990, Haavard Nord and Eirik Chambe-Eng (the original developers of Qt and the CEO and President, respectively, of The Qt Company) were working together on a database application for ultrasound images written in C++ and running on the classic Mac OS, Unix, and Microsoft Windows.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] They began development of "Qt" in 1991, three years before the company was incorporated as Quasar Technologies, then changed the name to Troll Tech and then to Trolltech.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] The toolkit was called Qt because the letter Q looked appealing in Haavard's Emacs typeface, and "t" was inspired by Xt, the X toolkit.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] The first two versions of Qt had only two flavors: Qt/X11 for Unix and Qt/Windows for Windows.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] On 20 May 1995 Trolltech publicly released Qt 0.90 for X11/Linux with the source code under the *Qt Free Edition License*.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] This license was viewed as not compliant with the free software definition by Free Software Foundation because, while the source was available, it did not allow the redistribution of modified versions.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Trolltech used this license until version 1.45.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Controversy erupted around 1998 when it became clear that the K Desktop Environment was going to become one of the leading desktop environments for Linux.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] As it was based on Qt, many people in the free software movement worried that an essential piece of one of their major operating systems would be proprietary.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] The Windows platform was available only under a proprietary license, which meant free/open source applications written in Qt for X11 could not be ported to Windows without purchasing the proprietary edition.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] With the release of version 2.0 of the toolkit in mid-1999, the license was changed to the Q Public License (QPL), a free software license, but one regarded by the Free Software Foundation as incompatible with the GPL.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Compromises were sought between KDE and Trolltech whereby Qt would not be able to fall under a more restrictive license than the QPL, even if Trolltech was bought out or went bankrupt.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] This led to the creation of the KDE Free Qt foundation, which guarantees that Qt would fall under a BSD-style license should no free/open source version of Qt be released during 12 months.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] In 2000, Qt/X11 2.2 was released under the GPL v2, ending all controversy regarding GPL compatibility.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] At the end of 2001, Trolltech released Qt 3.0, which added support for Mac OS X (now known as macOS).
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] The Mac OS X support was available only in the proprietary license until June 2003, when Trolltech released Qt 3.2 with Mac OS X support available under the GPL.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] In 2002, members of the KDE on Cygwin project began porting the GPL licensed Qt/X11 code base to Windows.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] This was in response to Trolltech's refusal to license Qt/Windows under the GPL on the grounds that Windows was not a free/open source software platform.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] The project achieved some success although it never reached production quality.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] This was resolved when Trolltech released Qt 4.0 also for Windows under the GPL in June 2005.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt 4 supported the same set of platforms in the free software/open source editions as in the proprietary edition, so it is possible, with Qt 4.0 and later releases, to create GPL-licensed free/open source applications using Qt on all supported platforms.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] The GPL v3 with special exception was later added as an added licensing option.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] The GPL exception allows the final application to be licensed under various GPL-incompatible free software/open source licenses such as the Mozilla Public License 1.1.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Nokia acquired Trolltech ASA on 17 June 2008 and changed the name first to Qt Software, then to Qt Development Frameworks.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Nokia focused on turning Qt into the main development platform for its devices, including a port to the Symbian S60 platform.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Version 1.0 of the Nokia Qt SDK was released on 23 June 2010.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] The source code was made available over Gitorious, a community oriented git source code repository, with a goal of creating a broader community using and improving Qt.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] On 14 January 2009, Qt version 4.5 added another option, the LGPL, to make Qt more attractive for both non-GPL open source projects and closed applications.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] In February 2011, Nokia announced its decision to discontinue Symbian technologies and base their future smartphones on the Windows Phone platform instead (and since then support for that platform has also been dropped).
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] In March 2011, Nokia sold the commercial licensing part of Qt to Digia, creating Qt Commercial.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] In August 2012, Digia announced that it would acquire Qt from Nokia.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] The Qt team at Digia started their work in September 2012.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] They released Qt 5.0 within a month and newer versions every six months with new features and additional supported platforms.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] In September 2014, Digia transferred the Qt business and copyrights to their wholly owned subsidiary, The Qt Company, which owns 25 brands related to Qt.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] In May 2016, Digia and Qt demerged completely into two independent companies.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt 5 was officially released on 19 December 2012.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] This new version marked a major change in the platform, with hardware-accelerated graphics, QML and JavaScript playing a major role.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] The traditional C++-only QWidgets continued to be supported, but did not benefit from the performance improvements available through the new architecture.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Qt 5 brings significant improvements to the speed and ease of developing user interfaces.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Framework development of Qt 5 moved to open governance at qt-project.org, which made it possible for developers outside Digia to submit patches for review.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Aside from The Qt Company, many organizations and individuals using Qt as their development platform participate in the open development of Qt via the Qt Project.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] One such Qt contributor is Klarälvdalens Datakonsult AB, a Swedish Qt consulting company.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] KDAB is involved in many areas, including maintenance of several components.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Together with RIM/BlackBerry, KDAB is maintaining the QNX and BlackBerry 10 ports of Qt.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] Another participator is Intel, contributing for example Wayland support.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] AudioCodes maintains IBM ClearCase support in Qt Creator.
[src:pyside-binding/qt-software] As a heavy user of Qt, the KDE project submits many patches and features from its developer library KDE Frameworks back to Qt.
